Session 5: Multivariate Analytics in R (I)

Collect the data we prepared in Python:

link='https://github.com/UWDataScience2020/data/raw/master/hdidemocia.RDS'
# a RDS file from the web needs:
myFile=url(link)

# reading in data:
fromPy=readRDS(file = myFile)

# reset indexes to R format:
row.names(fromPy)=NULL

Unsupervised ML: Clustering Techniques

In supervised techniques, the computer finds the patterns on its own, as the data does not contain an example for the algorithms. Lets explore three types of clustering approaches.

  1. Partitioning: You will request a particular number of clusters to the algorithm. The algorithm will put every case in one of those clusters. Outliers will affect output.

Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cluster_analysis

  1. Hierarchizing: You will ask the algorithm to find all possible ways cases can be clustered, individually and in subgroups following a tree-construction/deconstruction approach. You should determine the right amount of clusters.Outliers will affect output.

Source: https://quantdare.com/hierarchical-clustering/

  1. Based on Density

This approach will cluster cases as long as they are close to each other at a predetermined distance. You need to input the distance and the minimal amount of cases in a neighboorhood to be considered a cluster. The algorithm is not affected by outliers.

https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Cluster_analysis

For all cases, you need the DISTANCE MATRIX:

a. Subset the data frame:

dfClus=fromPy[,c(2,12,13)]

b. Rename the rows:

row.names(dfClus)=fromPy$Country
head(dfClus)
##             Humandevelopmentindex Civilliberties       Regimetype
## Norway                      0.954           9.71   Full democracy
## Switzerland                 0.946           9.12   Full democracy
## Ireland                     0.942          10.00   Full democracy
## Germany                     0.939           9.41   Full democracy
## Hong Kong                   0.939           8.53 Flawed democracy
## Australia                   0.938          10.00   Full democracy

c. Keep only complete data:

dfClus=dfClus[complete.cases(dfClus),]

d. Set random seed:

set.seed(999)

e. Decide distance method and compute distance matrix:

library(cluster)
dfClus_D=cluster::daisy(x=dfClus,metric="gower")

Partitioning technique

1. Apply function: you need to indicate the amount of clusters required.

NumCluster=4
res.pam = pam(x=dfClus_D,k = NumCluster,cluster.only = F)

2. Save clustering results.

dfClus$pam=as.factor(res.pam$clustering)

You can see who the members are:

row.names(dfClus[dfClus$pam==1,])
##  [1] "Norway"         "Switzerland"    "Ireland"        "Germany"       
##  [5] "Australia"      "Iceland"        "Sweden"         "Netherlands"   
##  [9] "Denmark"        "Finland"        "Canada"         "New Zealand"   
## [13] "United Kingdom" "Austria"        "Luxembourg"     "Spain"         
## [17] "France"         "Portugal"       "Chile"          "Uruguay"

Hierarchizing: agglomerative

1. Apply function: you need to indicate the amount of clusters required.

library(factoextra)

res.agnes<- hcut(dfClus_D, k = NumCluster,isdiss=T,
                 hc_func='agnes',
                 hc_method = "ward.D2")

2. Save clustering results.

dfClus$agn=as.factor(res.agnes$cluster)

You can see who are the members:

row.names(dfClus[dfClus$agn==1,])

Hierarchizing: divisive

1. Apply function: you need to indicate the amount of clusters required.

library(factoextra)

res.diana<- hcut(dfClus_D, k = NumCluster,
                 hc_func='diana',
                 hc_method = "ward.D")

Density-based clustering

library(fpc)

res.db = dbscan(dfClus_D, eps=0.05, MinPts=15,method = 'dist')

How many cluster were produced? and How many outliers are there?

# '0' identifies outliers: 
res.db
## dbscan Pts=164 MinPts=15 eps=0.05
##          0  1  2
## border 104  7 26
## seed     0 12 15
## total  104 19 41

Save result:

dfClus$db=as.factor(res.db$cluster)

How to compare clustering?

  • Prepare a bidimensional map:
projectedData = cmdscale(dfClus_D, k=2,add = T)
dfClus$dim1 <- projectedData$points[,1]
dfClus$dim2 <- projectedData$points[,2]
  • See the map:
base= ggplot(data=dfClus,
             aes(x=dim1, y=dim2,
                 label=row.names(dfClus))) 
base + geom_text(size=2)

  • Plot results from PAM:
pam=base + labs(title = "PAM") + geom_point(size=2,
                                              aes(color=pam),
                                              show.legend = F)
  • Plot results from Hierarchical AGNES:
agn=base + labs(title = "AGNES") + geom_point(size=2,
                                              aes(color=agn),
                                              show.legend = F)

Compare visually:

library(ggpubr)
ggarrange(pam, agn)

  • Plot results from DBSCAN:
db= base + labs(title = "DBSCAN") + geom_point(aes(color=db),
                                               show.legend = T) 
db

Annotating:

library(ggrepel)
db + geom_text_repel(size=3,aes(label=row.names(dfClus)))

Annotating outliers:

LABEL=ifelse(dfClus$db==0,row.names(dfClus),"")

db + geom_text_repel(aes(label=LABEL))
